<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=99787567956175></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f99787567956175><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj><a href=/strategy/races.html?race=6&mid=99787567956175>RE: use of practice points</a></span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Aug 15th 7:41 AM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Save practice points if you can.  You never know when they will come in handy (such as when you get a nice piercing weapon, but have spent your whole life using 1HB weapons), or with research.  I don't put anything into the magic-related skills because those will go up quickly on their own -- especially channeling.  You do need to put one point into meditate when you first get it (lvl 8 for wizards, I believe) just to 'learn the basics' but that also goes up quickly with use.<br><br>If you want to put a point into a trade skill to start off, it probably won't hurt, but I have noticed that the high INT of Erudites does wonders in that regard (went from nothing to lvl 8 in blacksmithing just by sharpening 6 rusty daggers using 12 stones).<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
